  <h1>Intensification Opportunities Proximal to Public Transport Nodes in Ballarat VIC</h1>
  <h2>Context</h2>
  <p>Ballarat is a fast-growing city in regional Victoria. Ballarat's population, <a href="https://data.ballarat.vic.gov.au/explore/dataset/ballarat-population/table/?sort=-year" target="_blank">measured at ~113,000 in the 2021 census</a>, is predicted to balloon to <a href="https://www.ballarat.vic.gov.au/property/ballaratgrowthareas" target="_blank">170,000 residents by 2041</a>. This steep population growth will require new housing solutions, as the city continues its transition from modest regional centre to major urban hub. As the State Government seeks to <a href="https://www.planning.vic.gov.au/planforvictoria/housing-for-all-victorians/housing-targets" target="_blank">"channel some growth away from Melbourne"</a> and build more homes <a href="https://www.planning.vic.gov.au/planforvictoria" target="_blank">"in regional Victoria in well-connected, well-serviced locations"</a>, Ballarat is anticipated to become a site of significant construction and redevelopment. As Ballarat's economy continues to <a href="https://www.ballarat.vic.gov.au/news/ballarats-economic-boom" target="_blank">grow and diversify</a> – bolstered by major infrastructure projects like the <a href="https://djsir.vic.gov.au/news-and-articles/momentum-builds-at-ballarat-west-employment-zone" target="_blank">Ballarat West Employment Zone</a> – housing will come under increasing pressure in the immediate term: new and relocating businesses will mean new jobs, which (in turn) attract new workers to the city, all of whom must be accommodated for within the housing stock.</p> 
<p> The City of Ballarat anticipates that an <a href="https://www.ballarat.vic.gov.au/ballarat-housing-strategy-2041" target="_blank">additional 29,000 homes</a> will be needed by 2014 to accommodate this growth.</p>
